guidance that creates equitable systemic change so all Texans can obtain effective,

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:32.059
efficient behavioral health care when and where they need it. So that is a mouthful, but we, in

00:03:32.059 --> 00:03:38.580
effect, are a think tank that makes policy recommendations and helps localities implement

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:47.220
policy changes around their mental health care system. We are Texas-focused. We, for most of the

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:51.139
history of the Institute, have been exclusively Texas-focused, but in the past few years have

00:03:51.139 --> 00:03:56.740
become more national in scope and even international a little bit in that we are taking

00:03:56.740 --> 00:04:01.619
things that we see that are working here and adding them to national conversations. So we have

00:04:01.619 --> 00:04:06.139
expanded some. Though, as you heard in the mission statement, we are still pretty Texas-focused.

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:11.259
Really, the organization's only been around for 10 years or so, a little bit less than that

00:04:11.259 --> 00:04:19.179
technically. And so it's not an old group, but it's been very productive in Texas, made a lot

00:04:19.179 --> 00:04:24.299
of changes, and things in the mental health system here are really getting better in large part, not

00:04:24.299 --> 00:04:31.739
exclusively, but in large part due to work of the Meadows Institute. The 130 or so people that

00:04:31.739 --> 00:04:35.899
work there now is the largest it's ever been. We continue to grow and have grown pretty rapidly

00:04:35.899 --> 00:04:41.420
in the past few years, but the data team is only, there's six of us that are full-time,

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:46.380
then we have a research assistant as well. So we're a pretty small chunk of the organization,

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:49.899
but we work across the organization, touch a whole lot of different things.

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:55.980
Basically, anything that has a quantitative flair to it, they're going to ask the data team to weigh

00:04:55.980 --> 00:05:05.339
in on. So we work on sort of all levels of projects and with all different sort of subgroups or teams

00:05:05.339 --> 00:05:11.579
within the Institute. We on the data team are primarily researchers and academics by background.

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:17.660
My boss, the Vice President of Population Health is a epidemiologist. It was a tenured professor

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:21.820
before she joined Meadows a couple of years ago, and she has built out the data team,

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:28.779
myself included, I joined about a year and a half ago. And we've been working with the data of the

00:05:28.779 --> 00:05:36.540
Institute for that period of time. Prior to that, it was a consulting firm that was on retainer that

00:05:36.540 --> 00:05:42.059
did all of the Institute's data work. And so we've been transitioning all of that in-house and building

00:05:42.059 --> 00:05:47.019
structures and processes around having all of that in-house, because it's a little bit different

00:05:47.019 --> 00:05:53.019
thing when you own it all yourself versus, or getting kind of discrete answers from an external

00:05:53.019 --> 00:06:00.299
partner. So I'll stop there. That was a lot already. Rachel, your last question was about me

00:06:00.299 --> 00:06:04.140
personally. Yeah, just curious to get to know you a little bit. What's something

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:10.940
fun you like to do outside of work? Sure. So I have a 15-month-old daughter. So outside of work

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:17.500
time, most of it goes to her. We're also expecting another little one in January. So we're a little

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:25.579
busy around here. But yes, it is. It is lots of fun. It is honestly not much free time, but as

00:06:25.579 --> 00:06:32.380
much joy as I can imagine. That's great. Well, thank you so much. We're so excited to have you here with

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:38.619
us today. It sounds like the data team is growing quite a bit. And with your new role, I'm curious,

00:06:38.619 --> 00:06:43.579
what does the year ahead look like? Or what's something you're most excited about in the next

00:06:43.579 --> 00:06:49.420
year? So we are growing. We don't have a position posted currently, but I could certainly see one

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:55.739
coming down the pipe. We are really, really kind of restructuring how we do all of our work.

00:06:55.739 --> 00:07:00.619
And we're organizing it a little bit differently than we have in the past. And that's, like I

00:07:00.619 --> 00:07:05.019
said, building those structures and processes has been a lot of the work that we've

00:07:05.019 --> 00:07:12.859
done sort of across our specific contracts or specific deliverable level projects. And so I'm

00:07:12.859 --> 00:07:19.420
really excited that we are going to have a kind of a more robust set of workflows and organizational

00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:26.059
processes in which people request data from us, request answers or analyses from us. And then also

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:32.059
the way in which we sort of function as a team, right? So like I said, we built from the ground

00:07:32.059 --> 00:07:37.820
up a little bit. We've only recently started to really fully utilize Git for version control.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:42.619
So that's kind of where we started from. We were in Dropbox sharing scripts via email to

00:07:42.619 --> 00:07:46.380
each other when I first joined. And so just building from the ground up. But I think

00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:53.019
those steps are going to make us more effective at the work we have been doing,

00:07:53.019 --> 00:07:58.059
but also allow us to kind of expand and do some more exploratory and kind of neat,

00:07:58.059 --> 00:08:02.700
I don't want to call it cutting edge, but like closer to the cutting edge kind of work.

00:08:04.619 --> 00:08:08.859
That's great. I see there's a few questions starting to come in on Slido and someone

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:14.459
had a great question. It said, super interesting to hear about the transition from using consultants

00:08:14.459 --> 00:08:19.500
to an in-house team. I'd love to hear about the infrastructure build and how you did it.

00:08:20.779 --> 00:08:25.739
Sure. That could easily take an hour itself. I will try not to make it that long. But

00:08:27.660 --> 00:08:31.899
when we came on, when the data team in-house started proper, like I said, when my boss

00:08:31.899 --> 00:08:35.979
joined a couple of years ago, there were a few things or a few pieces that the external

00:08:35.979 --> 00:08:44.059
consultants kind of owned and managed for the Institute. One was a big hospital database. So

00:08:44.059 --> 00:08:50.859
it's all admissions and all encounters at ERs, hospitals in the state of Texas, and the external

00:08:50.859 --> 00:08:57.099
team owned and managed this, you know, and sort of like kept all of that on their side, but they

00:08:57.099 --> 00:09:02.539
would provide answers, provide discrete answers out of that to the content teams in Meadows.

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:12.219
So we took all of that, brought it over, put it into AWS and built the kind of the structure for

00:09:12.219 --> 00:09:17.179
our analysis of it in-house totally differently than they had done it. So we had to like

00:09:17.179 --> 00:09:21.500
reinvent the wheel a little bit on that database. And that was a big part of the work. The other

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:27.659
one was the prevalence estimation that we do. So if you want to know how many people in County X

00:09:28.539 --> 00:09:34.619
are dealing with major depression, for example, we have a proprietary estimate that we developed

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.580
and that was owned by the consulting firm. We have now brought that over in-house as well.

00:09:40.299 --> 00:09:47.179
Moving all of those retrospective data and then the integration of new data as it comes in each

00:09:47.179 --> 00:09:55.020
year was a sizable task. I think if there's a lesson learned that I could take from that,

00:09:55.739 --> 00:10:00.140
it would just be that we have a good ongoing relationship with that external consulting firm

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:05.739
and that has been completely critical. We honestly couldn't have done it without that.

00:10:05.739 --> 00:10:11.099
If we had a, you know, like a cutoff or like an end date with them that was, you know,

00:10:11.099 --> 00:10:14.619
firm and they were going to answer no more questions to that point, we would be up a

00:10:14.619 --> 00:10:18.299
creek. And so the fact that we have been able to go back and forth with them and they can pull

00:10:18.299 --> 00:10:21.979
up old documents that, you know, maybe should have been shared, but weren't originally. And

00:10:21.979 --> 00:10:27.739
that kind of thing has been totally essential. So I hope that answers the question that wasn't

00:10:27.739 --> 00:10:32.299
too nitty-gritty, but basically if you can maintain that ongoing relationship in some way,

00:10:32.299 --> 00:10:36.700
even if it's just a small retainer in a few hours a month, I think it's probably worthwhile.

00:10:38.299 --> 00:10:43.900
Yeah, that's really helpful. I see somebody else asked, knowing how much public sentiment

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:50.140
affects what issues get attention, do you end up allying with news organizations to share data

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:57.580
and compelling story ideas? Yes. I don't know that allying is the right word exactly, and

00:10:57.580 --> 00:11:03.179
to be clear, that's not my end of the operation. So I can't speak to it perfectly, but yes,

00:11:03.179 --> 00:11:08.219
we are certainly aware that we need public sentiment to be with us on these important

00:11:08.219 --> 00:11:14.299
issues. And so we have press releases and we work on stories and we put out

00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:19.179
information in a variety of ways, and I will say a growing variety of ways. We're really starting to

00:11:19.179 --> 00:11:24.059
get to that place where we're going to have nationally focused stories that are coming out,

00:11:24.059 --> 00:11:28.219
where we're sort of making the case for the policies that we believe the research and the

00:11:28.219 --> 00:11:34.940
data support. Are you able to give us an example of one of the projects that your team's working on?

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:44.700
Sure. So at the institute level, one policy, one specific sort of mental health

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:48.619
intervention that we really believe in works and that the research really supports,

00:11:49.659 --> 00:11:54.460
honestly, incredibly strongly, it's called collaborative care, which in very brief is

00:11:54.460 --> 00:12:00.940
this idea that your PCP, your family doctor, your primary care physician is your main point

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:04.460
of contact for most of your health care. And they track things like your blood pressure,

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:08.619
not because they're necessarily the one who would do open heart surgery on you, but because they're

00:12:08.619 --> 00:12:12.940
the ones who keep track of all of this information. So collaborative care is just the idea that we can

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:16.859
bring mental health into that same sort of treatment space. So they'll track your blood

00:12:16.859 --> 00:12:21.979
pressure, but they'll also track your depression and anxiety symptoms. And then collaborative care

00:12:21.979 --> 00:12:25.900
says we build the system out from there. So the referral network starts from the PCP.

00:12:26.539 --> 00:12:30.780
They are getting supported by a psychiatrist. So they know when is the appropriate time to

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:34.780
refer to a psychiatrist, when is the appropriate time to refer to a social worker or a counselor.

00:12:35.340 --> 00:12:38.700
And then they also have somebody in house who's helping with those things and can do some of the

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:43.340
sort of more straightforward behavioral interventions that are possible in like an

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:49.979
outpatient PCP setting. So that's a very brief and rough description of the model, but that's

00:12:49.979 --> 00:12:53.020
the model. And generally, we think this is a good thing and should be supported.

00:12:53.659 --> 00:12:58.299
The Institute as a whole encourages this through, we're trying to get and have gotten

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:03.659
Medicare and Medicaid uptake of it, as well as private funders to pay for these things,

00:13:03.659 --> 00:13:07.099
because in health care, that's what you have to do. You have to move the funders to move the

00:13:07.099 --> 00:13:12.700
treatment. And then all the way down to the data team specifically, which I think is probably the

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:18.859
point of the question. The data team is there to help say, you know, a given county in Texas says,

00:13:18.859 --> 00:13:23.739
okay, you know, we see this, we understand, we want this model to be implemented in our county

00:13:23.739 --> 00:13:28.780
clinics, right, in the health care that we as a county provide. But we don't know how many people

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:32.780
are going to need each tier of care under collaborative care, right? How many people

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:36.539
are just going to be sort of getting checked on by their PCP? How many will need the counselor?

00:13:36.539 --> 00:13:42.299
How many will need a psychiatrist? And there's a lot of sort of gradation between those two.

00:13:42.299 --> 00:13:46.219
So then the data team will come in and work with the data that that county has

00:13:47.419 --> 00:13:52.700
from their health care provision over the past X number of years, and work out estimates using

00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:57.739
that data, our sort of foundational prevalence estimates that I talked about a minute ago,

00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:02.299
county data from other counties that are comparable. So we'll do some matching on that

00:14:02.299 --> 00:14:05.659
and say in other counties that have implemented this, here's how you might see this go.

00:14:06.539 --> 00:14:12.059
And so we're bringing together lots of data sources and analyzing them to, with the goal

00:14:12.059 --> 00:14:17.340
of getting to the answer of, okay, here's how you could plant a staff. Here's what you might need in

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:22.859
terms of funding for your local hospital to be able to implement this well, and how, if you're

00:14:22.859 --> 00:14:27.500
going to build out this program, the kinds of uptake you can expect over time, and where you

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:35.820
should, we would think you'd be in, say, five years. Thank you. And thinking of, like, all the different

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:42.619
problems that you're working on, how does a team prioritize? Do you have a process for that?

00:14:43.179 --> 00:14:50.780
Yeah, no, it's a challenge. So we do, we get a variety of requests. Some are contract level,

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:54.780
that's kind of what I was just talking about. If we're in an agreement with a particular health

00:14:54.780 --> 00:15:00.780
care system or a state or local government, some of them come from legislators, right? If a

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:05.739
legislator wants to know something, or our CEO thinks the legislator wants to know something,

00:15:05.739 --> 00:15:09.979
we're going to generate that estimate too, right? That's going to be an important number or set of

00:15:09.979 --> 00:15:16.380
numbers to share. And so those two things typically bubble to the top. We have to meet our deliverables,

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:21.099
and if there's a request that's going to go to some policymaker somewhere, we need to push

00:15:21.099 --> 00:15:26.700
on that, right? Those things, even if they have not been well planned in advance, which sometimes

00:15:26.700 --> 00:15:32.140
happens, those things need to get done so that they will be prioritized. I think if there is a

00:15:34.539 --> 00:15:39.500
thing that drops to the bottom that does not get priority, it's our exploratory work. And that's,

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:43.340
you know, that stinks. I'd love to spend more time doing that. We've got a really impressive

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:48.940
team of people, and I think we could really move the needle in terms of methods and analytic

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:55.419
answers. But we unfortunately don't have all the time that we want to do those things. So the

00:15:55.419 --> 00:16:02.299
priorities, to more directly answer the question, the priority list goes policymakers, contracts,

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:08.859
everything else. Thank you. I just wanted to mention, because I know I always say this in

00:16:08.859 --> 00:16:14.539
the very beginning and not everybody's on yet, but you can use Slido to ask questions, which

00:16:14.539 --> 00:16:19.500
Hannah just shared in the chat. But you can also raise your hand here on Zoom if you want to jump

00:16:19.659 --> 00:16:25.580
in and talk to us live, or put questions into the Zoom chat too, and I can call on you.

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:35.500
But another Slido question was, how has the focus on 988, mobile crisis teams or community-based

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:41.500
stabilization, for example, impacted your organization and or your work on the data team?

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:48.059
And for people who aren't familiar with what that means, 988, would you be able to share that too?

00:16:49.020 --> 00:16:55.659
Sure. 988 is a national number that is now up and operational that is sort of equivalent

00:16:55.659 --> 00:17:01.580
to 911, but specific for mental health needs, suicidality specifically. So if somebody is

00:17:01.580 --> 00:17:08.140
feeling suicidal and needs help immediately, they can call 988 instead of 911 and get that help.

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:12.060
So whoever asked that question is well-informed, and that is absolutely a thing we're thinking

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:20.939
about and working on. It is all complicated, right? The different communities that we work

00:17:20.939 --> 00:17:25.260
with, and again, we're primarily Texas-focused, so the different communities have different levels

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:31.339
of sort of uptake and buy-in of these things and of mobile crisis outreach teams, or MCOTs is what

00:17:31.339 --> 00:17:38.459
we call them. And we believe in the methods, the approach, the intervention I think is strong,

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:43.900
but you can't force communities to buy into these things, right? So it's about providing the

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:49.900
information, providing the guidance when there is interest, and supporting the implementation when

00:17:49.900 --> 00:17:57.180
the time comes. But in terms of how we work with that, it is about collecting and curating the data

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:02.939
to show what we think it will continue to show, which is that these are positive programs. These

00:18:02.939 --> 00:18:09.099
programs work well and support people, and making a clear and compelling empirical case for that

00:18:09.099 --> 00:18:14.459
is sort of our task on the data team. So how does the implementation of a mobile crisis outreach

00:18:14.459 --> 00:18:18.939
team in a community impact that community? We're the ones who are going to be helping to calculate

00:18:18.939 --> 00:18:26.060
that. I've not worked too closely on that particular line of questioning, but in general,

00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:31.339
we're going to be the ones who are trying to quantify the value of these things, both in terms

00:18:31.339 --> 00:18:37.020
of real value, like improving people's lives, but also financial value or return on investment.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:45.020
That return on investment question comes up quite a bit, so I'm just curious,

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:51.739
how do you actually calculate that? It is complicated. We have some economists

00:18:51.739 --> 00:18:56.540
laying around who help with these things. I'm a psychologist by background, so that is not my area.

00:18:56.780 --> 00:18:59.660
I actually trained as a family therapist originally, so I'm

00:19:00.219 --> 00:19:06.300
sort of a long way away from the data and have sort of slowly made my way over, but our

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:13.500
economists bring in as many factors as we can come up with to try to

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:20.699
understand that there's going to be a ramp-up cost, the building of the program

00:19:20.699 --> 00:19:23.979
that is typically going to be really expensive, and you're not going to be seeing

00:19:24.780 --> 00:19:30.300
the return immediately, so you're going to be at a loss most likely in the early days,

00:19:30.300 --> 00:19:35.739
but building that over time in terms of both population growth as well as changes in prevalence

00:19:35.739 --> 00:19:41.500
and need, once you factor all these things in and you take it out five, 10 next years, you can

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:46.859
start to see the actual return on investment through reduced emergency room use, because

00:19:46.859 --> 00:19:55.339
emergency room use is really, really expensive. Improved taxpayer base,

00:19:55.339 --> 00:20:01.099
there are more people who are able to contribute to their communities if they're not in

00:20:01.099 --> 00:20:08.219
prison or in a psychiatric bed. There are also more people who are available to support

00:20:08.219 --> 00:20:14.699
that system, so as you start that flywheel, it picks up speed and peer support can

00:20:14.699 --> 00:20:20.140
jump in and take a lot of people some of the way, is how I should say that,

00:20:20.859 --> 00:20:26.060
so that you really end up kind of building a self-maintaining system, and the costs go down,

00:20:26.060 --> 00:20:34.140
but the return stays there. Thank you. I love getting to hear when people come from different

00:20:34.140 --> 00:20:39.339
backgrounds and end up in this data and analytics space. I'm just curious, what was your journey

00:20:39.339 --> 00:20:45.660
getting here? Yeah, it's a funny one. So, I started as a family therapist, like I said,

00:20:45.660 --> 00:20:52.140
practicing clinically, and my idea was that I was going to do that for the rest of my career. When

00:20:52.140 --> 00:20:58.780
I started graduate school, that was the thought. I realized pretty quickly that it is really

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:04.939
challenging work. I was working in low-income clinics and working with child abuse cases and

00:21:04.939 --> 00:21:09.660
things like that, and it's really hard work, and my heart goes out to anybody who does it

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:15.579
full-time, but I thought I'd like to have some diversity to my experience, right? I don't want

00:21:15.579 --> 00:21:20.300
to just be practicing clinically. I want to do other things, so I went to a PhD program in human

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:25.500
development. It was sort of like a social psych-developmental psych hybrid, is how you

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:32.060
could think about it, and I was in that program, still practicing clinically, but getting

00:21:32.060 --> 00:21:36.859
research training and getting data training. I started sort of learning at my advisor's knee on

00:21:36.859 --> 00:21:44.459
SAS, doing data work, and I was just sort of enthralled by it. So, I taught myself some SAS,

00:21:44.459 --> 00:21:48.459
and then I learned about R, and I picked it up, and I started running with it because it was

00:21:48.459 --> 00:21:57.260
more fun than SAS to me. So, then my post-graduate school career, I worked in research and evaluation

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:02.540
roles in academia, but I was always kind of the most data-focused person on the team, and then you

00:22:02.540 --> 00:22:08.459
start to, you start to polarize, right? You, as the most data-focused person, you get the data asks,

00:22:08.459 --> 00:22:11.900
and then you learn that, how to do that particular thing, and you polarize a little further, and then

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:15.979
you're more data-focused than you were the last time, right? So, as projects come in, you just

00:22:15.979 --> 00:22:21.979
kind of polarize to one side, or that's what happened to me anyway, and at this point,

00:22:21.979 --> 00:22:25.900
my clinical experience is still useful. Like, I work for a mental health policy institute, so that

00:22:26.219 --> 00:22:31.979
is valuable to have a clinically licensed person working with the data. I can speak to what it is

00:22:31.979 --> 00:22:37.180
like to be in the room, and to sit with someone who is suicidally depressed, or with a family that

00:22:37.180 --> 00:22:41.739
is really, really struggling, and so that is valuable, but I don't practice clinically anymore.

00:22:41.739 --> 00:22:47.979
I just bring that in, you know, through the data, and through, you know, how I read the data,

00:22:47.979 --> 00:22:52.219
right? The numbers mean something a little bit different to me, I think, because of that experience,

00:22:52.619 --> 00:23:00.060
and so, yeah, so now I'm really almost exclusively data-focused, but I still have that sort of

00:23:00.699 --> 00:23:06.219
heart background of the family therapist. Yeah, that's such a good point. I imagine that's

00:23:06.219 --> 00:23:12.540
incredibly helpful to understanding the data. I see, Caitlin, you put a question to the Zoom chat.

00:23:12.540 --> 00:23:18.939
Do you want to jump in? Sure, I hope you guys can hear me okay. I'm in a cafe, but I was recently

00:23:19.099 --> 00:23:24.140
wondering what do you kind of envision for the future of mental health care and data science,

00:23:24.140 --> 00:23:28.380
because I always compare this kind of to bioinformatics, that there's kind of a whole

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:34.859
discipline for biology and data science, and then human genomics, so I wonder what you kind of

00:23:34.859 --> 00:23:39.819
envision for the future of mental health and data science, and if you think behavioral sciences will

00:23:39.819 --> 00:23:45.979
ever almost kind of catch up to kind of genomics, and more of the physical life sciences?

00:23:49.099 --> 00:23:55.020
Thank you, Caitlin. That's an awesome question. I like that a lot, and I am hopeful that we're on

00:23:55.020 --> 00:24:00.459
that same trajectory. I don't know about catch up, just because, you know, they've got a head start,

00:24:00.459 --> 00:24:07.660
right, but I think there is definitely growth in that area for behavioral science, and that we can

00:24:07.660 --> 00:24:15.260
certainly move towards more sort of the biostats side of biology, right, have a more quantitative

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:22.300
focus. We're pretty large in our focus here. We generally focus on populations rather than

00:24:22.300 --> 00:24:26.540
individuals, but at the individual level, I'll say one thing that I think is coming and that will

00:24:27.739 --> 00:24:33.819
change mental health and behavioral science broadly is computer adaptive testing for mental

00:24:33.819 --> 00:24:39.819
health concerns. So, you know, if you've taken the GRE, or I'm sure lots of other standardized tests

00:24:39.819 --> 00:24:45.739
do it too, but it's, as you answer a question, the computer adapts your next question based on

00:24:45.739 --> 00:24:51.020
whether you got it right or wrong. So, it's sort of targeting towards your ability, right, your

00:24:51.020 --> 00:24:57.020
level of knowledge on whatever that test is, and those, they're very, very effective at sort of

00:24:57.020 --> 00:25:01.900
honing in on where a person actually sits on a level of knowledge of that subject that they're

00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:07.739
testing on, but in mental health, we ask lots of survey questions, right? We ask people, the PHQ-9

00:25:07.739 --> 00:25:14.140
is the standard measure for measuring depression in most populations, and so there are nine

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:18.060
questions, but right now, they're static, right? Everybody gets the same nine questions every single

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:22.459
time they respond to that, and the questions don't vary at all according to how you answered

00:25:22.459 --> 00:25:27.660
one or two or three. If you bring computer adaptive testing into that space, you can make,

00:25:27.660 --> 00:25:33.260
one, reduce participant burden enormously, so you have, you don't have to ask as many questions,

00:25:33.260 --> 00:25:38.060
right? You can use AI to sort of generate models that will help to inform based on how somebody

00:25:38.060 --> 00:25:42.060
answers question one, whether they need eight more questions or whether they only really need

00:25:42.060 --> 00:25:48.540
two more questions, right? So, it reduces participant burden. It makes the output more

00:25:48.540 --> 00:25:52.619
precise, right? So, we don't have just sort of a single number, but we have a single number for

00:25:52.619 --> 00:25:57.339
all the people who fit into that really precise category of people answering those questions in

00:25:57.339 --> 00:26:03.099
that particular way or in that pattern of responses, and then it also allows us to,

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:08.619
once you integrate computer adaptive testing, you're kind of inherently integrating that into,

00:26:09.579 --> 00:26:14.540
maybe not your EHR, but into your data world, right, into your data system. A lot of PHQ-9s

00:26:14.540 --> 00:26:19.020
are done on paper, right? So, you walk into your counselor or your psychiatrist's office,

00:26:19.020 --> 00:26:22.140
and you might fill out a form on paper and hand it back to them. They'll look at it

00:26:22.140 --> 00:26:26.459
and use that information, but once you go to computer adaptive testing, you have made the

00:26:26.459 --> 00:26:31.260
leap into sort of the digital collection of that information, which allows us to connect it to

00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:36.540
everything else, right, the ability to connect those responses over time within that person,

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:41.819
but also for that, you know, whole community, for everyone being served there and to understand what

00:26:41.819 --> 00:26:46.859
is effective for each of these, you know, really precise subgroups of people in terms of how they

00:26:46.859 --> 00:26:52.140
respond to this. So, sorry, I'm a little passionate about computer adaptive testing. I don't know if

00:26:52.140 --> 00:26:55.979
you can tell, but I just, I think there's a whole lot of potential there, and that's just one,

00:26:56.540 --> 00:27:01.180
one, like, in the broader world you're kind of talking about, which is moving towards,

00:27:02.380 --> 00:27:08.619
you know, more advanced quantitative and scientific work on these things. Behavioral science is

00:27:08.619 --> 00:27:12.540
unfortunately behind on those things, but I do hope we're going in that direction.

00:27:12.540 --> 00:27:16.219
Does that help? Do you have a specific, like, thought or question around that?

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:19.260
No, no, I love that answer, and that's really great to hear.

00:27:23.660 --> 00:27:30.540
Thank you. This is kind of related. So, on that, on that topic where you said, like,

00:27:31.579 --> 00:27:39.020
behavioral science is behind on, in that in general, why do you think, like, certain industries

00:27:39.900 --> 00:27:44.300
can take such a long time to get into, like, data and analytics?

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:51.099
That is, that is interesting. I'll speak to healthcare because it's a good example of an

