industry that's, that's lagged on that. Yeah. And it's also the only one I really, I know very well.

00:27:56.540 --> 00:28:03.579
So, in, in healthcare, the systems are largely, not, not exclusively, but, but largely

00:28:03.579 --> 00:28:08.540
outdated and kind of archaic, and they're slow to pick up new things. Part of the issue

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:12.859
in my view is, is the regulation around them, right? There's a ton of regulation,

00:28:13.579 --> 00:28:19.180
HIPAA and high-tech and otherwise, around how these systems have to be built and maintained,

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:24.300
and, and for lots of good reason, right? There's, it's not that, that regulation is completely

00:28:24.300 --> 00:28:29.339
unwarranted. It's information that should be protected and handled carefully. But there,

00:28:29.339 --> 00:28:35.420
there is, I used to work with an attorney who is a national expert in HIPAA, and he would say,

00:28:35.420 --> 00:28:40.380
you know, it's, it ends up most of the time just being an excuse, right? It's not that the law

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:45.260
actually forbids this thing from happening, but it is a very, very good excuse to hide behind for,

00:28:45.260 --> 00:28:52.540
for pushing the boundaries or extending into, into new areas. And so, you know, I think that is

00:28:52.540 --> 00:28:56.060
probably right. That has been my experience where people will just say, we can't do that because of,

00:28:56.060 --> 00:29:02.939
because of HIPAA, because of high-tech. And I, I wish it was, it was clear that there is

00:29:02.939 --> 00:29:06.540
flexibility even within those rules and that those rules are, are, people are revising them,

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:11.339
right? There's, there's new stuff coming out. There's going to be new policies released because

00:29:11.339 --> 00:29:16.140
we're in a different world now than we were when they were written. And so working, working towards

00:29:16.140 --> 00:29:21.579
a place where we are, you know, not, not afraid to make changes, but, but respecting the data as

00:29:21.579 --> 00:29:27.020
we need to while also kind of pushing boundaries and being willing to, to take some chances with

00:29:27.660 --> 00:29:33.420
new technologies. It seems like that's a balance we have not quite struck properly yet.

00:29:35.900 --> 00:29:41.660
It kind of reminds me of like that idea of like not being able to submit to the FDA,

00:29:41.660 --> 00:29:48.219
but how that's changing and then how our idea around HIPAA is changing. I see Logan,

